05620nam a22009255i 9781487533793DE-B159720230127011820.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230127t20202020onc    fo  d z      eng d  a97814875337937 a10.3138/97814875337932doi  a(DE-B1597)545078  a(OCoLC)1131818774  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aonccCA-ON 4aPQ4087b.Z56 2020 7aLIT0042002bisacsh04a850.9/00912231 aZiolkowski, Saskia Elizabeth, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aKafka’s Italian Progeny /cSaskia Elizabeth Ziolkowski. 1aToronto : bUniversity of Toronto Press, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (312 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aToronto Italian Studies00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Kafka, World Literature, and the Italian Literary Landscape -- t1. Amerika in Italy: Kafka’s Realism, Pavese, and Calvino -- t2. Dreams of Short Fiction after Kafka: Lalla Romano, Giorgio Manganelli, and Antonio Tabucchi -- t3. Processi without End: The Mysteries of Dino Buzzati and Paola Capriolo -- t4. Kafka’s Parental Bonds: The Family as Institution in Italian Literature -- t5. The Human-Animal Boundary, Italian Style: Kafka’s Red Peter in Conversation with Svevo’s Argo, Morante’s Bella, and Landolfi’s Tombo -- tEpilogue: Calvino’s Kafka and Kafka’s Italy -- tWorks Cited -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWhile many scholars of world literature view national literary traditions as resolved and stable, Kafka’s Italian Progeny takes the fluid identity of the modern Italian tradition as an opportunity to reconsider its dimensions and influencers. Exploring a distinct but unexamined Kafkan tradition in modern Italian literature, it brings Italian literary works into larger debates and reorients the critical view of the Italian literary landscape. The book calls attention to the way Kafkan themes, narrative strategies, and formal experimentation appear in a range of Italian authors. Offering new perspectives on familiar figures, such as Italo Calvino, Italo Svevo, and Elena Ferrante, it also sheds light on some lesser-known authors, including Tommaso Landolfi, Paola Capriolo, and Lalla Romano. Using diverse approaches to explore thematic, generic, historical, and cultural connections between Kafka’s works and those of Italian authors, the author argues for a new view of Italian literature that includes talking animals, parental bonds, modernist realism, literary detective novels, and lyrical microfiction. Whereas Kafka has been mobilized in discourses on minor and world literature, Kafka’s Italian Progeny investigates the particular nature of the Italian reception of Kafka to reveal the richness and variety of modern Italian literature.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Jan 2023) 0aItalian literaturey20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / Italian.2bisacsh  aElena Ferrante.  aElsa Morante.  aItalian literature.  aItalian studies.  aItalo Calvino.  aItalo Svevo.  aKafka.  aLalla Romano.  aPaola Capriolo.  aTommaso Landolfi.  acomparative literature.  aliterary history.  aworld literature.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural, Area Studies 2020 Englishz978311070474708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural, Area Studies 2020z9783110704532oZDB-23-DKU08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2020z97831106904530 c